  "solution": {
    "format": "pdf-layout-text",
    "rawText": "A simple way to decide between the four given options is to determine which of the points (1, 0),\n(−1, 0), (0, 1) and (0, −1) lie on the graph.\nWe start with (1, 0): this gives 1 × 1 = 1, so (1, 0) lies on the graph. We now look at (0, 1): this\ngives 1 × 1 = 1, so this also lies on the graph. On the other hand, (−1, 0) gives −1 × 1 = −1\nand (0, −1) gives the same, so neither of these points lies on the graph.\nTherefore the graph must be that shown in option C.\nAlternatively, we can multiply out the brackets, giving x3 + y 3 = 1; therefore for large values\nof x, we must have y 3 ≈ −x3 or y ≈ −x, giving A or C. Now when 0 < x < 1, we must have\n0 < y < 1, and hence the correct graph is C.\n\n\n\n\n                                                10\n                                                                                       © UCLES 2019"
  },
